This one is for our FL Studio gang! ⁣
⁣
This stock FL Studio plugin lets you see which notes are being played in complicated audio material. It doesn’t work on everything, but it can be very helpful in studying chords, vocals, and other tonal samples!⁣
⁣
Also helpful for figuring out the key of your samples!⁣
⁣
If this one helps, share with an FL Studio friend!⁣

node.text:
😱 This is an important one to understand!

Many of the popular FX plugins only come with a dry / wet knob.

Understanding what happens to your signal when increasing this knob is important!

We gain the effect at the expense of the original source sound. So we add reverb, but lose original synth sound (in this example).

This can take away some volume, transients, upfront feeling, high end, etc.

You may not want that!! What if the sound needs to remain transient, bright, up front, etc? Think of a snare that needs reverb...or even a vocal!

By using a send and return, you can keep those characteristics AND add the reverb!! This adds the “wet” to the “dry” without losing any dry volume/signal.

Understanding when and where to use both comes down to first understanding what is actually happening to your signal.

Hopefully this helps and makes sense, and now you can make better judgment on which way you’d want to use it for each sound in your mix. ♥️

Tap the ❤️ and fix the clicks and pops in your chopped audio ✂️
⁣
⁣
I never like to take any tip for granted!! Although many might know this one, I'm still surprised how many times I see this issue pop up in a student's song during our 1-on-1's!⁣
⁣
⁣
Simply put, you can't just chop audio wherever you please haha. You technically CAN, but there could be artifacts that come along with it.⁣
⁣
⁣
Ever notice these small clicks or pops whenever your sample starts / finishes? That's because of the way you cut your clip.⁣
⁣
⁣
When cutting audio, you should try and aim for a "zero crossing" point aka where the audio crosses that center line.⁣
⁣
⁣
This is easy to find/do when a signal is mono because there's only one waveform to cut (even if its a mono signal split to a L&R channel they are mirrored).⁣
⁣
⁣
This becomes a little trickier with stereo information because the Left and Right channel might not be crossing the "Zero" at the same point...⁣
⁣
⁣
Using FADES is ideal in these situations because it allows you to smoothly fade in, or out, of your audio. It will literally make your audio start or finish at a zero crossing point.⁣
⁣
⁣
⁣

To some, this might be laughable...DONT HATE! There was a day where YOU didn't know this!⁣
⁣
⁣
Are you in the process of LEARNING scales? This helps.⁣
⁣
⁣
It's hard when you start anything for the first time and this trick absolutely ease the process!⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣
⁣
Creating a song in a certain scale (e.g. Gminor)? Look up which notes are in that scale and place stickers on all of those keys, across the octaves. This will now clearly show you which keys you can press to stay in that scale.⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣
⁣
This should allow you to have more confidence when "jamming out," which is EXTREMELY important.  It's hard to just pencil in melodies all the time. Many of the best creations come from mistakes, and experimentation. These markers will allow you to do just that, and keep you under control and in key!⁣
⁣
⁣
*Some DAW's have a feature which will allow you to stay in the scale (even if you play a "wrong" note). These are cool, but they don't actually teach you which notes are correct while playing :(

node.accessibility_caption: Are you making this common eq mistake while producing?
Should every sound have its own space in the mix?
This is 100% true but we need to understand how this applies to EQ
Steep filters and eq shapes look good but sound unnatural
Think of an orchestra.  There is plenty of overlap
Volume is the mixing tool we use to separate competing sounds
Steep filter shapes can sound unnatural.  They are hard to fit sounds together
Use gradual filter shapes.  Choose sounds that compliment each other rather than overlap.
Steep slopes can be used in mastering or group processing.
Hope this helps
